# Railway deploy for `vesta-web`

## Source repository (prevents “regression” / old UI)

- Service **`vesta-web`** → Settings → **connected GitHub repo** must be **`boctavian2014-ux/Vesta-AI`**, not **`boctavian2014-ux/vesta-web`**. The standalone `vesta-web` repo is legacy; active product code lives under this monorepo in **`web/`**.
- After any repo switch, trigger a deploy and confirm the deployment shows a **recent commit SHA** from `Vesta-AI`.

## Build context (monorepo)

- Deploy the Node app from **`web/`** only.
- CLI from machine: `railway up . --path-as-root --service vesta-web --environment production` run **inside** [`web/`](web/).
- Do not use **monorepo root** as build root without Option A or B: detectors may pick **Python** and still run `npm run build` → **`npm: not found`** (exit **127**).

### Option A — Root Directory + Nixpacks / Railpack (typical GitHub deploy)

- **Root Directory:** `web`
- Uses [`web/railway.json`](web/railway.json) and [`web/nixpacks.toml`](web/nixpacks.toml) when builder is Nixpacks.
- **Do not** set Root Directory = `web` while using repo-root [`Dockerfile.vesta-web`](Dockerfile.vesta-web) — that Dockerfile expects `COPY web/...` from **repo root** (Option B).

### Option B — Dockerfile from repo root

- **Root Directory:** empty (repo root).
- **Dockerfile path:** `Dockerfile.vesta-web`

## Verify production

- Open `view-source:` on [https://vesta-asset.com/](https://vesta-asset.com/) and check `./assets/index-*.js`: the **hash** should change after real frontend deploys. Same hash as before + old UI → still serving a previous successful deployment or wrong repo.
- Build log **SUCCESS** alone does not prove the domain updated; confirm **Deploy** tab and **commit** on that deployment.

## Yellow warning / failed deploys

- **Variables:** no empty variable names, no malformed `KEY=value` lines (Railway can reject or break deploy).
- Read **Deploy / runtime logs**, not only **Build** (crash on start, wrong `PORT`, etc.). [`web/server/index.ts`](web/server/index.ts) listens on `process.env.PORT` (Railway sets this).
